{
  "text": "Let \u03d5, \u03c8 \u2208 N and n \u2265 2. A sequence (z 1 , . . . , z n ) of points in R d is called a descending chain in (\u03d5, \u03c8) if z i \u2208 \u03d5 for odd i \u2208 {1, . . . , n}, z i \u2208 \u03c8 for even i \u2208 {1, . . . , n} and z i prefers z i+1 to z i\u22121 for each i \u2208 {2, . . . , n \u2212 1}. Note that any pair (z 1 , z 2 ) \u2208 \u03d5 \u00d7 \u03c8 is a descending chain. An infinite sequence (z 1 , z 2 , . . .) of points in R d is called an infinite descending chain if for every n \u2265 2, (z 1 , . . . , z n ) is a descending chain. The following result can be proved as Lemma 15 in [CITATION_1] . Lemma 2.2. Let \u03d5, \u03c8 \u2208 N, and suppose that there is no infinite descending chain in (\u03d5, \u03c8). Then \u03d5 \u221e = \u2205 or \u03c8 \u221e = \u2205, and there is a unique stable partial matching from \u03d5 to \u03c8, which is produced by the mutual nearest neighbor matching. Remark 2.3. In d = 1, there is no infinite descending chain in (Z, \u03c8) for any \u03c8 \u2208 N. Otherwise there would be an infinite descending chain in Z. The corresponding statement does not hold for any d > 1. For later use we define the the matching status of a point as the (measurable) function",
